	The New York Times is engaged in a comprehensive effort to track the details of every coronavirus case in the United States, collecting information from federal, state and local officials around the clock. The numbers in this article are being updated several times a day based on the latest information our journalists are gathering from around the country. The Times has made that data public in hopes of helping researchers and policymakers as they seek to slow the pandemic and prevent future ones.



	See our maps tracking the coronavirus outbreak around the world.



	As some places reopen, outbreaks surge elsewhere



	In South Carolina, department stores and flea markets were allowed to reopen on Monday. In Florida, some beaches have welcomed back visitors. And in Georgia, residents will be able to leave home for a haircut, a workout or even a fresh tattoo later this week.



	This measure will apply statewide and will be the operational standard in all jurisdictions, Gov. Brian Kemp of Georgia, a Republican, said on Monday. This means local action cannot be taken that is more or less restrictive.



	Indeed, there were hopeful signs in some parts of the country, including New York, where the governor predicted the worst was over; in San Francisco, where the rate of new cases has stabilized; and in Seattle, where the once-bleak outlook improved to the point that a field hospital was deconstructed and shipped elsewhere.












